According to figures released this week by independent research and consultancy firm ETFGI, inflows into global exchange-traded products (ETPs) so far this year have already exceeded those of the whole of 2016. A record level of $391.21 billion in net inflows made it into ETPs in the first seven months of 2017.This includes money invested into both exchange-traded funds (ETFs) and exchange-traded notes (ETNs) in 69 exchanges across 56 countries.In July alone global ETPs received net inflows of $43.48 billion. This marked 41 consecutive months of positive inflows into these products.Total assets invested in ETPs across the world at the end of July reached $4.279 trillion, representing a year-on-year growth rate of 20.6%. At the same time last year, total assets in ETPs was $3.548 trillion.The compound annual growth rate for these products over the whole of the last decade is 19.4%.Of the 20 ETFs that have received the largest inflows so far in 2017, 16 track equity indices. The remaining four are bond funds, with three of them specifically tracking corporate bond indices.The largest net inflows have gone into three BlackRock products the iShares Core S&amp;P 500 ETF, iShares Core MSCI EAFE ETF and iShares Core MSCI Emerging Markets ETF.Together, these three effectively cover most of the world&#8217;s equity markets. The S&amp;P 500 ETF tracks the iconic US index, while the MSCI EAFE ETF tracks an index of developed markets excluding the USA and Canada. The MSCI Emerging Markets ETF covers over 20 emerging markets, including South Africa.The expense ratios on these three products range from 0.4% to 0.14%.Only four of the 20 fastest growing funds are listed outside of the US. All of them are equity funds listed in Japan. Three of them track the Tokyo Price Index (TOPIX), while one tracks the Nikkei 225.